Sure, here's an example of generating a table of contents in LaTeX using the `tocmath` package and the `tableofcontents` environment:
```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocmath} % for automatic section numbering
\begin{document}
% Define sections to include in table of contents
\section{Introduction}
\section{Methodology}
\section{Results}
\section{Discussion}
\end{document}
```
In this example, we first load the `tocmath` package which provides automatic section numbering for the table of contents. We then define our sections as usual with `\section`. Finally, we create the main document body without any additional formatting or content.
To generate the table of contents, we use the `tableofcontents` environment from the `natbib` package (which is loaded by default). This environment creates a table of contents based on the section headings in the document. To do so, it scans the document looking for all occurrences of the command `\section`, counts them, and generates a table of contents with appropriate labels. 
The resulting table of contents will look like this:
```
1 Introduction
2 Methodology
3 Results
4 Discussion
```
Note that the numbers in parentheses are not part of the output; they just indicate where each section starts in the input file. Also note that if you have multiple levels of subheadings (`\subsection`, etc.), those will also be included in the table of contents.

